                    Q1. Why can't Two Pointers be applied directly to an unsorted array?
                    L5 Answer
                    
                            "The Two Pointer technique relies on the array being ordered. 
                            In a sorted array, moving the left pointer to the right increases the value,
                            while moving the right pointer to the left decreases the value. 
                            This predictable behavior allows us to eliminate part of the search space. 
                            In an unsorted array, moving either pointer has no predictable effect 
                            on the sum, so we can't determine which direction to move."

                      ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

                  Q2. If we sort first, would you use Two Pointers?

  
                            Sorting an array generally takes:  O(n log n)                            
                            Then Two Pointers take:  O(n)
                            
                            Total:  O(n log n + n)

                            Simplified:
                            
                            O(n log n)
                  Interview Answer
                  
                                "Yes. If modifying the input is allowed, I would first sort the array in O(n log n) time and 
                                  then apply the Two Pointer technique in O(n). The overall time complexity becomes O(n log n), 
                                with the extra space depending on the sorting algorithm used."
                  
      

                  Q3. If original indices must be returned, can you still sort?
                  Your Answer  : No.
                  
                  Verdict : ✅ Correct.
                  
                  Excellent.  However...
                  
                  Google interviewer follow-up: "Are you sure?"

                Actually...   You can sort if you store the original indices.
                
                Example:

                      Instead of sorting:  [11,2,7,15]
                      
                      you sort pairs:   (value,index)

                          (2,1)                          
                          (7,2)                          
                          (11,0)                          
                          (15,3)
                          
                      Now Two Pointers still work. When you find the answer, you return the stored indices.
                          
               SO ANSWER IS :      
                   "If I sort the original array directly, I'll lose the mapping between values and their original indices. 
                    However, if sorting is permitted, I can instead sort value-index pairs. 
                    That preserves the original indices while still allowing the Two Pointer technique."

            This is a very common senior-level follow-up.
            
            Q4. Do duplicates break the algorithm?
          L5 Answer

                "Yes. The algorithm still works because it relies on the sorted order, not on the uniqueness of elements. 
                  Duplicate values don't affect the rule that moving the left pointer increases or maintains the current value, 
                  while moving the right pointer decreases or maintains it. Therefore, the correctness of the algorithm is preserved."



        INTERVIEW TWIST    : Now let me challenge you with something Google interviewers love.
        
        Suppose I say:       
                         nums = [1,2,2,2,3,4,5]
                                        
                          target = 4

                Now I ask:    Return ALL unique pairs.
                
                Would your current Two Pointer algorithm work?



Step 1: Clarifying Questions

                A strong candidate would first ask:
                
                Is the array already sorted?
                Should I return values or indices?
                By unique, do you mean unique values or unique indices?

Usually, interviewers mean unique values, so the answer should contain only:

Step 2: Can the Existing Two Pointer Algorithm Work?

                The answer is:  Yes, but it needs one modification.
                
                The basic algorithm still works because the array is sorted.
                
                The only additional step is:  After finding a valid pair, skip all duplicate values before continuing.

Correct Algorithm

When

sum == target
Save the pair.
Move the left pointer past all duplicate values.
Move the right pointer past all duplicate values.
Continue searching.

                public List<List<Integer>> findUniquePairs(int[] nums, int target) {
                
                    List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
                
                    int left = 0;
                    int right = nums.length - 1;
                
                    while (left < right) {
                
                        int sum = nums[left] + nums[right];
                
                        if (sum == target) {
                
                            result.add(List.of(nums[left], nums[right]));
                
                            int leftValue = nums[left];
                            int rightValue = nums[right];
                
                            while (left < right && nums[left] == leftValue) {
                                left++;
                            }
                
                            while (left < right && nums[right] == rightValue) {
                                right--;
                            }
                
                        } else if (sum < target) {
                
                            left++;
                
                        } else {
                
                            right--;
                
                        }
                    }
                
                    return result;
                }



Complexity

                        Time Complexity

                Each pointer moves only forward (or backward) through the array.
                Even when skipping duplicates, each element is visited at most once.

                Time: O(n)
                
                Space:
                
                Ignoring the output list: O(1)
                Including the returned pairs: O(k), where k is the number of unique pairs.

L5 Interview Answer

                If I asked this in an interview, this is the kind of explanation I'd expect:
                
                "The standard Two Pointer approach still works because the array is sorted. However, if the requirement is to 
                return only unique pairs, I need to avoid reporting the same value pair multiple times. After finding a valid pair, 
                I would record it and then advance both pointers past any duplicate values before continuing the search.
                This ensures each unique pair is reported exactly once while maintaining an O(n) time complexity."
